This study revealed multiple spatial and temporal fluctuations of
from the three neighbouring villages in south-eastern Tanzania,
and confirmed the presence of pyrethroid, DDT and bendiocarb
resistance in each of these three villages. The substantial, though
not absolute reversal of pyrethroid and carbamate resistance when
mosquitoes were pre-exposed to PBO or TPP, coupled with the
resistance alleles, suggests involvement of P450
monooxygenases and esterases as key determinants confer-
ring the resistance phenotypes. We recommend further intensity
bioassays to determine the strength of phenotypic resistance, as
well as biochemical and molecular analysis to elucidate various
enzymes involved in the resistance. Such additional tests are essen-
tial for an effective resistance management programmes in this or
similar areas. Overall, these results highlight the importance of
periodic and continuous insecticide susceptibility surveillance
and emphasize the need to consider fine-scale variations in
insecticide resistance levels, even in small geographical locations,
